1
00:01:42,800 --> 00:01:44,000
Whoa!

2
00:01:53,500 --> 00:01:55,200
All the food's gonna go bad.

3
00:01:57,800 --> 00:01:59,100
Yeah, I drew up a list.

4
00:01:59,200 --> 00:02:02,400
I'll hit the store
before it gets all bought out.

5
00:02:05,100 --> 00:02:06,100
Fuck.

6
00:02:06,200 --> 00:02:08,700
- Can you save it?
- No. No way.

7
00:02:08,800 --> 00:02:11,399
No, I gotta start over from scratch.

8
00:02:11,400 --> 00:02:13,700
I'll call the studio
when the phones get back up,

9
00:02:13,800 --> 00:02:15,400
see if they can extend my deadline.

10
00:02:16,600 --> 00:02:18,300
What choice do they have?

11
00:02:21,000 --> 00:02:22,000
You kiddin'?

12
00:02:22,001 --> 00:02:24,800
They could whip up some bad
Photoshop poster in an afternoon.

13
00:02:24,900 --> 00:02:27,200
They do it all the time.
Two big heads.

14
00:02:27,300 --> 00:02:29,276
I should have brought it downstairs
with me last night.

15
00:02:29,300 --> 00:02:30,900
Just stupid, I guess.

16
00:02:31,000 --> 00:02:33,000
Well, sweetie,
you couldn't exactly know

17
00:02:33,100 --> 00:02:35,076
that a tree was gonna come flying
through the window.

18
00:02:35,100 --> 00:02:36,576
Yeah, I'll hit the hardware store too,

19
00:02:36,600 --> 00:02:38,120
get some plastic sheeting
and duct tape

20
00:02:38,200 --> 00:02:40,399
and seal this up
before it gets dark, you know.

21
00:02:40,400 --> 00:02:42,000
Order in some new glass.

22
00:02:43,500 --> 00:02:44,860
Oh, you know what?
That was your...

23
00:02:44,900 --> 00:02:47,400
that was your grandfather's tree,
the one he planted.

24
00:02:47,500 --> 00:02:50,200
- Ohh.
- Used to play in that tree.

25
00:02:50,300 --> 00:02:51,500
It's just stuff, though.

26
00:02:51,600 --> 00:02:54,000
You know, we're safe.
That's all that counts.

27
00:02:54,100 --> 00:02:55,200
Yeah.

28
00:02:55,300 --> 00:02:56,900
Mom, Dad, you gotta come see!

29
00:02:57,000 --> 00:02:58,700
Hey, Billy, take it easy, all right?

30
00:02:58,800 --> 00:03:00,576
I really don't want you running
all over the place.

31
00:03:00,600 --> 00:03:01,699
But you gotta come look.

32
00:03:01,700 --> 00:03:04,799
The boathouse is all bashed!
Holy crap!

33
00:03:04,800 --> 00:03:05,999
Billy.

34
00:03:06,000 --> 00:03:09,100
Sorry, Mom, but you just
gotta come! Come on!

35
00:03:09,200 --> 00:03:10,500
Whoa!

36
00:03:10,800 --> 00:03:12,000
Whoa.

37
00:03:12,100 --> 00:03:14,099
- Whoa.
- Come on.

38
00:03:14,100 --> 00:03:16,099
Having spoken,
the Doomsayer departs.

39
00:03:16,100 --> 00:03:18,700
Come on!

40
00:03:18,800 --> 00:03:20,800
How do you two always manage
to make me laugh?

41
00:03:21,800 --> 00:03:24,500
- You have incredibly low standards.
- Mm-hmm.

42
00:03:24,600 --> 00:03:27,600
Let's go, uh, see the damage.

43
00:03:27,700 --> 00:03:28,700
No.

44
00:03:33,700 --> 00:03:35,800
- Norton's tree.
- Yeah.

45
00:03:37,300 --> 00:03:39,200
You mean the dead one
I've been asking him

46
00:03:39,300 --> 00:03:41,499
to take down for three years
before it finally blew over?

47
00:03:41,500 --> 00:03:42,500
That tree?

48
00:03:43,700 --> 00:03:46,800
- Really got smooshed.
- You ain't kiddin'.

49
00:03:48,200 --> 00:03:49,800
Look at that.

50
00:03:52,200 --> 00:03:53,300
What is it, Daddy?

51
00:03:54,300 --> 00:03:55,300
Mist.

52
00:03:56,800 --> 00:03:59,700
- On the lake?
- We've had mist on the lake before.

53
00:03:59,800 --> 00:04:01,700
Coming off the mountain like that?

54
00:04:01,800 --> 00:04:04,300
Two fronts meeting,

55
00:04:04,400 --> 00:04:06,600
left over from the storm,
something like that.

56
00:04:06,700 --> 00:04:08,100
You sure?

57
00:04:08,200 --> 00:04:09,600
Honey, I'm not the weatherman.

58
00:04:09,700 --> 00:04:11,900
Why don't you take Billy,
get him dressed.

59
00:04:12,000 --> 00:04:13,300
I'll take him to town with me.

60
00:04:13,400 --> 00:04:14,700
Okay. Where you going?

61
00:04:14,800 --> 00:04:17,900
I'm gonna go have a little chat
with our neighbor about his tree.

62
00:04:18,000 --> 00:04:19,100
Hon.

63
00:04:19,200 --> 00:04:21,199
Don't worry, I'm not gonna
punch him in the nose.

64
00:04:21,200 --> 00:04:22,500
You know what he's gonna say.

65
00:04:22,600 --> 00:04:25,699
He's gonna say, "Sue me,"
which, I don't know, maybe we should.

66
00:04:25,700 --> 00:04:30,200
Honey, one property dispute with
this guy is enough to last me a lifetime.

67
00:04:30,300 --> 00:04:33,200
I'm gonna ask
for his insurance information.

68
00:04:33,300 --> 00:04:35,000
- Okay.
- That's all.

69
00:04:35,100 --> 00:04:36,400
Yeah.

70
00:04:39,100 --> 00:04:41,500
Ohh!
Mother fucker!

71
00:04:44,600 --> 00:04:46,099
Aw, shit!

72
00:04:46,100 --> 00:04:48,600
Ohh, you mother fucker!

73
00:04:49,900 --> 00:04:51,000
Cock sucker!

74
00:04:53,100 --> 00:04:54,199
"Turn on.

75
00:04:54,200 --> 00:04:56,400
"Full choke.

76
00:04:56,500 --> 00:04:58,700
Pull five... choke."

77
00:05:03,100 --> 00:05:04,600
I guess you've seen the...

78
00:05:06,100 --> 00:05:07,199
boathouse.

79
00:05:07,200 --> 00:05:08,500
Yeah, and...?

80
00:05:08,600 --> 00:05:10,299
Nothin'.

81
00:05:10,300 --> 00:05:13,600
Just think we should trade
insurance info, you know?

82
00:05:13,700 --> 00:05:14,800
That's all.

83
00:05:17,400 --> 00:05:20,000
Oh, my insurance guy's
gonna <i>love</i> me.

84
00:05:22,800 --> 00:05:24,100
Oh.

85
00:05:24,200 --> 00:05:26,200
Shit. The 1980.

86
00:05:26,300 --> 00:05:28,100
I was gonna bring
the station wagon, but...

87
00:05:29,600 --> 00:05:33,700
I don't know, the weather was so beautiful coming
out of New York, I just... you know, top down.

88
00:05:33,800 --> 00:05:35,600
I'm sorry, man. I mean it.

89
00:05:35,700 --> 00:05:37,100
Sincerely.

90
00:05:38,800 --> 00:05:41,400
- That's nice of you to say.
- No, that car was cherry.

91
00:05:41,500 --> 00:05:43,200
I hate to see it like that.

92
00:05:46,100 --> 00:05:47,600
Okay, I'll tell you what,

93
00:05:47,700 --> 00:05:50,500
I'll find my insurance guy's number,
I'll bring it by later.

94
00:05:50,600 --> 00:05:52,100
- That okay?
- No problem.

95
00:05:58,400 --> 00:05:59,500
So, uh, David...

96
00:06:01,300 --> 00:06:04,600
you're not heading into town today
by any chance, are you?

97
00:06:19,600 --> 00:06:22,100
Well, CMP's out in force.

98
00:06:22,200 --> 00:06:23,700
Maybe we'll get our power back.

99
00:06:23,800 --> 00:06:25,800
I know. Some storm, huh?

100
00:06:25,900 --> 00:06:27,200
One for the books, yeah.

101
00:06:27,300 --> 00:06:28,999
For a moment there last night,

102
00:06:29,000 --> 00:06:31,499
I thought we were gonna take off
and head for Oz.

103
00:06:31,500 --> 00:06:33,600
WZON is off the air,

104
00:06:33,700 --> 00:06:35,800
but Portland's still broadcasting.

105
00:06:35,900 --> 00:06:38,800
- Daddy, look.
- Ah.

106
00:06:38,900 --> 00:06:40,500
Guys from the base.

107
00:06:40,600 --> 00:06:42,700
- From up the mountain?
- Uh-huh.

108
00:06:42,800 --> 00:06:44,200
The Arrowhead Project?

109
00:06:46,000 --> 00:06:48,799
Well, you're a local.
Any idea what they do up there?

110
00:06:48,800 --> 00:06:50,399
Missile defense research...

111
00:06:50,400 --> 00:06:52,200
You know, I'm sure
you've heard the stories.

112
00:06:52,300 --> 00:06:53,399
Oh, sure.

113
00:06:53,400 --> 00:06:55,800
The woman at the Laundromat
says that, uh,

114
00:06:55,900 --> 00:06:59,000
they have a crashed flying saucer
up there with frozen alien bodies.

115
00:06:59,100 --> 00:07:00,800
Right. Miss Edna. Yeah.

116
00:07:00,900 --> 00:07:03,400
Miss Tabloid.

117
00:07:03,500 --> 00:07:06,200
"I Had Bigfoot's Baby."

118
00:07:07,500 --> 00:07:10,000
"Satan's Face Appears
in Oil Well Fire."

119
00:07:10,100 --> 00:07:11,500
You know, real reliable stuff.

120
00:07:16,200 --> 00:07:17,700
Well, they're in a hurry.

121
00:07:17,800 --> 00:07:19,400
Maybe their power's out too.

122
00:07:28,400 --> 00:07:29,600
Huh. Still no signal.

123
00:07:29,700 --> 00:07:32,900
Why don't you go ahead?
I'm gonna try Steph on a pay phone.

124
00:07:33,000 --> 00:07:34,700
Can I go with Mr. Norton, Daddy?

125
00:07:34,800 --> 00:07:37,500
Sure, if you promise
to hold his hand, I guess.

126
00:07:37,600 --> 00:07:38,600
- Yeah.
- Yeah.

127
00:07:38,700 --> 00:07:40,300
Here's a list.

128
00:07:40,400 --> 00:07:41,700
- Sure.
- Okay?

129
00:07:41,800 --> 00:07:43,000
Meet you guys in there.

130
00:07:45,000 --> 00:07:46,300
Hold hands.

131
00:07:49,800 --> 00:07:52,200
I'm sorry.
I didn't know it was your sister.

132
00:07:56,700 --> 00:07:58,700
Those look <i>so</i> freaky!

133
00:07:58,800 --> 00:07:59,800
Hmm.

134
00:08:07,600 --> 00:08:09,400
- Sally, hey.
- Hey, Mr. Drayton.

135
00:08:09,500 --> 00:08:10,800
You guys look jammed up.

136
00:08:10,900 --> 00:08:14,000
Yeah, well, half the staff
didn't show, plus the power's out.

137
00:08:14,100 --> 00:08:16,400
Oh, no. What, no backup generator?

138
00:08:16,500 --> 00:08:18,000
Only to keep the food cold.

139
00:08:18,100 --> 00:08:21,000
Everything else, welcome to the Dark Ages,
and bring your checkbook.

140
00:08:21,100 --> 00:08:23,800
Hey, Thursday night,
Steph and I want a date night.

141
00:08:23,900 --> 00:08:26,000
- Baby-sit?
- Heck, yeah. I'm there.

142
00:08:27,400 --> 00:08:28,500
Oh, my God.

143
00:08:28,600 --> 00:08:30,199
The storm.

144
00:08:30,200 --> 00:08:33,200
Everybody's stockin' up.
Been like this since we opened.

145
00:08:33,300 --> 00:08:34,600
Crappy day, huh?

146
00:08:34,700 --> 00:08:37,000
Eh, everyone's a little
pissed off this morning.

147
00:08:37,100 --> 00:08:39,000
'Morning, Mrs. Carmody.

148
00:08:40,100 --> 00:08:42,700
With lines like these,
I don't know how good it is,

149
00:08:42,800 --> 00:08:45,000
but I guess we'll have to make do.

150
00:08:46,000 --> 00:08:48,500
- Keep your head down, pal.
- I know it.

151
00:08:52,200 --> 00:08:53,300
Hey, champ.

152
00:08:54,500 --> 00:08:55,800
Your wife should be a doctor.

153
00:08:55,900 --> 00:08:58,260
She could make a fortune
in Manhattan with this handwriting.

154
00:08:58,300 --> 00:09:00,900
Yeah, it takes some getting used to.

155
00:09:01,000 --> 00:09:03,176
Why don't you get your stuff?
I'll meet you at the checkout.

156
00:09:03,200 --> 00:09:04,200
Okay, done.

157
00:09:07,000 --> 00:09:10,100
Hey, David,
thanks for helping me out today.

158
00:09:13,900 --> 00:09:16,400
Are you and Mr. Norton
gonna be friends now, Daddy?

159
00:09:16,500 --> 00:09:20,800
Oh, I don't know.
"Friends" might be stretching it a little.

160
00:09:21,800 --> 00:09:24,200
I guess you're not mad
at each other anymore.

161
00:09:24,300 --> 00:09:25,499
I guess not.

162
00:09:25,500 --> 00:09:28,800
Hey. And that's a start, huh?

163
00:09:29,800 --> 00:09:31,900
I'm sorry, ma'am,
the registers are down.

164
00:09:32,000 --> 00:09:33,800
The power outage got us too.

165
00:09:33,900 --> 00:09:36,600
Hopefully we'll have
power up pretty soon.

166
00:09:46,400 --> 00:09:49,100
- The bus leaves in 30 minutes.
- We'll make it, okay?

167
00:09:49,200 --> 00:09:51,500
You guys get the goodies.
I'll wait in line.

168
00:09:53,200 --> 00:09:55,500
Yes, ma'am, those are $1.25.

169
00:09:56,500 --> 00:09:58,700
I need some change on register five.

170
00:10:00,200 --> 00:10:02,100
Good morning, Ms. Reppler.

171
00:10:02,200 --> 00:10:03,600
Hello, Ms. Reppler.

172
00:10:03,700 --> 00:10:07,900
Well, hello to you, Billy Drayton.
How'd you hold up in the storm?

173
00:10:08,000 --> 00:10:12,000
We had a tree come through the picture
window last night, right in my studio.

174
00:10:12,100 --> 00:10:15,900
And the boathouse got all smooshed.
Mr. Norton's tree fell on it.

175
00:10:16,000 --> 00:10:17,300
- Ouch.
- Yeah.

176
00:10:17,400 --> 00:10:20,000
Sorry to hear that.

177
00:10:21,600 --> 00:10:22,900
How'd you guys make out?

178
00:10:23,000 --> 00:10:26,100
Oh, we're fine.
It's the listings I'm worried about.

179
00:10:26,200 --> 00:10:29,040
At the very least, I'll bet every one
of our "For Sale" signs fell over.

180
00:10:29,100 --> 00:10:31,800
We had damage
at the school, wouldn't you know?

181
00:10:31,900 --> 00:10:34,800
That's what we get for not fixing
that roof when we should've,

182
00:10:34,900 --> 00:10:38,300
but with funds being cut every year...

183
00:10:38,400 --> 00:10:42,500
You'd think educating children would
be more of a priority in this country,

184
00:10:42,600 --> 00:10:44,400
but you'd be wrong.

185
00:10:44,500 --> 00:10:47,700
Government's got better things
to spend our money on,

186
00:10:47,800 --> 00:10:51,400
like corporate handouts
and building bombs.

187
00:11:05,000 --> 00:11:06,700
Daddy, is there a fire?
Is Mommy all right?

188
00:11:06,800 --> 00:11:09,400
I'm sure she's fine.
Don't worry, okay?

189
00:11:10,400 --> 00:11:11,900
Mind what you're doing, Sally.

190
00:11:12,900 --> 00:11:14,500
Oh, come on,
we got 10 days' leave.

191
00:11:14,600 --> 00:11:15,699
Check our papers.

192
00:11:15,700 --> 00:11:17,699
Look, I told you,
all leaves are cancelled.

193
00:11:17,700 --> 00:11:18,800
I don't know why.

194
00:11:18,900 --> 00:11:20,800
I gotta go check the pharmacy out.

195
00:11:20,900 --> 00:11:23,300
Three men meet me
back at the Jeep in five minutes.

196
00:11:23,400 --> 00:11:24,600
That's an order.

197
00:11:27,000 --> 00:11:30,500
Shit, man! Another half an hour,
and we'd have been gone.

198
00:12:03,700 --> 00:12:05,200
Oh, my God!

199
00:12:13,600 --> 00:12:14,999
Something in the mist!

200
00:12:15,000 --> 00:12:18,400
Something in the mist took John Lee!

201
00:12:18,500 --> 00:12:19,800
Dan, catch your breath.

202
00:12:19,900 --> 00:12:21,800
Something in the mist took John Lee.

203
00:12:21,900 --> 00:12:23,600
I could hear him screaming.

204
00:12:23,700 --> 00:12:26,600
Shut the doors! Shut the doors!
My God!

205
00:12:26,700 --> 00:12:28,400
Daddy, I'm scared.
Can we go home?

206
00:12:32,800 --> 00:12:33,899
Don't go out there.

207
00:12:33,900 --> 00:12:36,199
There's something in the mist.
It took John Lee.

208
00:12:36,200 --> 00:12:38,700
Screw that!
I'm gettin' in my car.

209
00:12:38,800 --> 00:12:40,300
Mister, no!

210
00:13:03,200 --> 00:13:04,500
Oh, shit.

211
00:13:12,600 --> 00:13:14,100
Please hold me.

212
00:13:14,200 --> 00:13:16,199
It's okay, it's okay.

213
00:13:16,200 --> 00:13:20,300
It's a pollution cloud.
The mills down in Rumford.

214
00:13:20,400 --> 00:13:23,500
Some kind of chemical explosion.
Has to be.

215
00:13:24,900 --> 00:13:26,400
What is it?

216
00:13:27,600 --> 00:13:29,100
What's going on?

217
00:13:32,300 --> 00:13:33,500
It's death.

218
00:13:34,500 --> 00:13:35,500
Aah!

219
00:14:08,300 --> 00:14:10,700
Stay down!

220
00:14:11,900 --> 00:14:13,000
Daddy!

221
00:14:19,800 --> 00:14:22,000
You all right? You okay?

222
00:14:32,200 --> 00:14:33,700
That was an earthquake.

223
00:14:34,700 --> 00:14:37,000
I tell you, the goddamn mills blew up!

224
00:14:37,100 --> 00:14:40,600
Is everyone okay?
Is anyone hurt?

225
00:14:40,700 --> 00:14:43,900
Everybody just stay put, okay?
Just stay inside the store.

226
00:14:44,000 --> 00:14:46,900
I can't. I can't stay here.
I gotta get home to my kids.

227
00:14:47,000 --> 00:14:50,000
No.
No, don't go out there.

228
00:14:50,100 --> 00:14:52,900
It's death out there.
It's the end of days.

229
00:14:53,000 --> 00:14:55,000
Stop it, okay? Stop it.

230
00:14:55,100 --> 00:14:57,900
Please, everybody,
everybody just relax, okay?

231
00:14:58,000 --> 00:14:59,999
He's right. Let's just stay cool.

232
00:15:00,000 --> 00:15:01,476
Let's just try to figure out
what happened.

233
00:15:01,500 --> 00:15:05,900
I'm sorry, I... I can't just stay here.
I have to get home to my kids.

234
00:15:06,000 --> 00:15:07,800
Ma'am, no, you can't go out there.

235
00:15:07,900 --> 00:15:09,600
Could be a poisonous gas cloud.

236
00:15:09,700 --> 00:15:11,200
Didn't you hear that man screaming?

237
00:15:11,300 --> 00:15:13,900
I agree. Let's stay here
until we figure it out.

238
00:15:14,000 --> 00:15:15,400
You're not listening!

239
00:15:16,100 --> 00:15:17,600
I can't stay here.

240
00:15:18,800 --> 00:15:22,600
Wanda's looking after little Victor.
She's only eight.

241
00:15:22,700 --> 00:15:27,000
Sometimes she forgets
she's supposed to be watching him.

242
00:15:30,700 --> 00:15:32,900
I told them I'd only be gone
a few minutes.

243
00:15:34,100 --> 00:15:36,400
She's only eight.

244
00:15:37,500 --> 00:15:40,300
For their sakes, don't.

245
00:15:45,500 --> 00:15:48,000
Well, isn't anybody gonna help me?

246
00:15:50,600 --> 00:15:52,500
Shh. It's okay, pal.

247
00:15:53,600 --> 00:15:56,200
Won't somebody here see a lady home?

248
00:16:01,200 --> 00:16:02,400
You?

249
00:16:10,000 --> 00:16:11,000
You?

250
00:16:20,600 --> 00:16:22,799
- It's okay, buddy.
- You?

251
00:16:22,800 --> 00:16:26,100
Ma'am, please,
I got my own boy to worry about.

252
00:16:30,400 --> 00:16:32,799
I hope you all rot in hell.

253
00:16:32,800 --> 00:16:35,100
Ma'am, please, wait until...

254
00:17:10,200 --> 00:17:12,700
Okay,
let's start cleaning up, okay?

255
00:17:12,800 --> 00:17:15,400
Get the spilled bottles,
